- **Cost efficiency**: Private series use same master infrastructure (£50-150k vs separate structure)
- **£40m retained seconds** problem solved (Series 2026-A, -B, -C etc.)
- **Balance sheet optimization**: Can later sell Series A/B/C notes to private credit

**Innovation:** Few UK issuers do this systematically within master issuer

#### **3. Technology Integration**

**Economic uses traditional monthly reporting; Polaris could modernize:**

**Blockchain-Enabled Reporting:**

- Partner with technology provider (e.g., Provenance, Capexmove)
- Real-time loan-level data access for investors
- Smart contract-based waterfall automation (informational, not legally binding)

**Cost:** £200-300k initial, £75k annual
**Benefit:**

- Investor relations premium (early adopter status)
- 3-5bps pricing benefit from transparency
- Operational efficiency (reduce manual reporting costs)

**Precedent:**

- Societe Generale has done blockchain RMBS (2019)
- Fitch has blockchain-based surveillance tools
- **First specialist lender master issuer** to integrate would generate significant market attention

-----

## RATING AGENCY CONSIDERATIONS: ECONOMIC VS POLARIS

### **Economic’s Rating Profile**

**Economic Master Issuer series typically:**

- **Fitch rated** (primary)
- **Moody’s** on some series
- **Not S&P** (Economic relationship-specific)

**Typical structure:**

- AAA: 75-78% of capital structure
- AA: 8-10%
- A: 5-7%
- BBB/Subordinated: 7-10%
- Credit enhancement: 5.5-8.5% depending on pool

### **Polaris Rating Strategy**

From screenshot, Polaris uses **dual rating (S&P + Fitch)** - this is optimal for master issuer:

**Recommended Approach:**

**Programme-Level Rating:**

- **Fitch and S&P** joint rating (already established relationship from legacy deals)
- One-time programme assessment: £350-450k
- Establishes master issuer creditor hierarchy, structural features
- **Benefit:** All series automatically “pre-assessed” for structure

**Series-Level Rating:**

- Each series: **Dual-rated by Fitch and S&P**
- Cost per series: £100-150k (vs £200-280k for new issuer)
- **Fast-track**: 4-6 weeks (vs 8-12 weeks new issuer)

**Moody’s Optional:**

- Consider adding Moody’s for **Series 1** only (programme launch credibility)
- Cost: +£150-200k Year 1, +£50-75k subsequent series
- **Benefit:** Triple-rating can reduce cost of funds 3-8bps
- **Decision:** Worth it if targeting US investors heavily

### **Credit Enhancement Efficiency**

**Economic’s approach (which Polaris should replicate):**

Each series independently credit-enhanced based on that pool’s characteristics:

**Example:**

```
Series 2026-1 (Conservative Pool):
├─ LTV: 68% WA
├─ ICR: 155% WA
├─ Geography: 50% London, 30% SE, 20% Regional
├─ Fitch AAA CE: 5.2%
└─ S&P AAA CE: 5.5%
   → Required CE: 5.5% (higher of the two)

Series 2026-2 (Aggressive Pool):
├─ LTV: 74% WA
├─ ICR: 140% WA
├─ Geography: 25% London, 35% SE, 40% Regional
├─ Fitch AAA CE: 7.1%
└─ S&P AAA CE: 7.8%
   → Required CE: 7.8%

Economic Benefit:
Series 2026-1: Can issue 94.5% AAA notes (efficient)
Series 2026-2: Can issue 92.2% AAA notes (higher subordination, appropriate to risk)

vs Traditional Shelf Approach:
All deals get "programme-wide" CE (typically worst-case), leaving 92% AAA across all deals regardless of pool quality (inefficient for conservative pools)
```

**Polaris can optimize this:**

- **Accumulate conservatively** in strong markets → maximize AAA issuance
- **Accumulate aggressively** in weak markets → accept higher subordination

